Here‚Äôs a comparison of why a bank might choose to license a third-party regulatory platform like CUBE versus building its own in-house regulatory management system:

‚∏ª

Why Banks Choose Third-Party Solutions like CUBE
	1.	Speed to Market
	‚Ä¢	CUBE already has a mature product with global regulatory coverage, reducing time to deployment.
	‚Ä¢	Avoids the long and costly development cycle of building an internal system from scratch.
	2.	Global Regulatory Coverage
	‚Ä¢	Tracks 1000+ regulators in 70+ languages across jurisdictions ‚Äî something very hard to replicate internally.
	‚Ä¢	Keeps up with evolving regulatory changes in real-time.
	3.	Advanced AI Capabilities
	‚Ä¢	Built-in NLP, graph learning, and regulatory ontology trained on financial regulation-specific data.
	‚Ä¢	Banks would struggle to train and validate such models effectively without dedicated regulatory data science teams.
	4.	Integration Ready
	‚Ä¢	Easily integrates with GRC tools, policy systems, and internal audit frameworks.
	‚Ä¢	Comes with APIs, dashboards, alerts, and audit logs.
	5.	Proven Compliance Expertise
	‚Ä¢	Developed by domain experts with legal, compliance, and financial backgrounds ‚Äî not just technologists.

‚∏ª

Why a Bank Might Build Its Own Model Instead
	1.	Full Customization
	‚Ä¢	Tailor the solution to its unique operating model, risk taxonomy, and internal controls.
	‚Ä¢	Greater control over taxonomy, risk appetite thresholds, and internal workflows.
	2.	Data Sensitivity & Confidentiality
	‚Ä¢	Some banks may be hesitant to expose sensitive compliance data to third parties, even under strict contracts.
	‚Ä¢	In-house systems can align closely with internal data governance policies.
	3.	Cost Considerations Over Time
	‚Ä¢	High upfront build cost, but lower ongoing license fees compared to vendor lock-in.
	‚Ä¢	Potential savings in the long term if scaled and maintained well.
	4.	Competitive Differentiation
	‚Ä¢	Proprietary models could become an edge in risk management or internal innovation showcases.
	5.	Local Regulatory Nuances
	‚Ä¢	In-house teams may better understand region-specific practices or internal audit expectations.

‚∏ª

Balanced View
	‚Ä¢	Many large banks opt for a hybrid model ‚Äî leveraging third-party platforms like CUBE for regulatory intelligence, and building internal layers for mapping, visualization, or control testing.

